I read through the first chapter and have time now to deliver the feedback I promised.

I usually only read short stories but for 7k words it didn't feel that long. It kept me reading the whole way through wanting to know what would happen next. The scenes where the main Bridgette took control in comforting or lecturing the protagonist on his importance to them were the best parts.

I think there's a lot for you to improve on though. Not a lot really happens over the chapter. The characters' personalities and actions don't affect the direction of the story as much as I'd like.

I understand central theme is The Company and the Bridgebots have deprived humanity of agency but I'd like to see the humans accidentally overstep their boundaries more or have the Bridgettes coerce and manipulate the humans in subtle, unexpected ways.

For example the ping pong scene shouldn't be just there to kill time. Sure, real prison has a lot of time killing but a story needs more.
Some interesting ideas could be that The Company has ordered the Bridgebots to foster socialization and cooperation among inmates and the Bridgebots. Bridgette assesses that the main character has less chance of rehabilitation among the other inmates so she chooses to bind him to her instead.

Your scenes need more direction and better anticipation going from one to the next. You can see what I'm talking about with the chapter's end. Even though Bridgette and the MC are closer there's no hint or foreshadowing what might come next. You probably have more planned than the MC simply serving out the rest of his term. Sow some of those seeds now!

On the other hand it would've been nice if the MC expressed more enthusiasm about his journey away from civilization as a response to the exposition you needed to deliver. This would've been a great place for subtle foreshadowing!
